Exercices Session III: Description and between-group comparisons

Applied Biostatistics Course with R

Author

Biostatistics Support and Research Unit, IGTP

Note

The DIVINE project contains data collected from subjects hospitalized in 5 hospitals in the southern metropolitan area of Barcelona during four waves of COVID-19. The divine dataset included in this exercise is a random sample of 1000 patients with some selected information from the 1st and 5th waves.

1. Read the divine.xlsx excel.

library(readxl)
divine <- read_excel("Data/divine.xlsx")

2. Find:

  1. The minimum, 1st quartile (25th percentile), median, mean, 3rd quartile (75th percentile) and maximum of each numerical variable. Also report the missing values for these variables.
Tip

The summary() function returns all these basic descriptive statistics, along with the number of missing values.

  1. Based on these values, which numerical variables are non-normally distributed?
Tip

Normally distributed variables should have a median close to the mean. If we find differences, it means that the variable is not normal.

Leukocytes and PCR do not distribute normally.

  1. Use QQ-Plot to confirm that the other variables are normally distributed.
Tip

Normally distributed variables should have points near the diagonal line.

library(ggplot2)

#Age
ggplot(data = divine, aes(sample = age)) +
  stat_qq() +
  stat_qq_line()
#Weight
ggplot(data = divine, aes(sample = weight)) +
  stat_qq() +
  stat_qq_line()
#Height
ggplot(data = divine, aes(sample = height)) +
  stat_qq() +
  stat_qq_line()
#Hemoglobin
ggplot(data = divine, aes(sample = hemoglobin)) +
  stat_qq() +
  stat_qq_line()

3. Describe all the variables stored in this dataset by COVID-19 wave. Report missing values, insert the appropriate labels for each variable, and choose the appropriate statistic for each numeric variable.

Tip
tbl_summary() allows you to create a description table for your data. We can change the default labels and statistics with the label and statistic functions. Remember to use the syntax below: 
library(gtsummary)

divine |> 
  tbl_summary(
    include = -record_id,
    by = covid_wave,
    label = list(
      center ~ "Hospital",
      sex ~ "Sex",
      age ~ "Age",
      weight ~ "Weight",
      height ~ "Height",
      obesity ~ "Obesity",
      dm ~ "Diabetes mellitus",
      total_leukocytes ~ "Total leukocytes",
      hemoglobin ~ "Hemoglobin",
      c_reactive_protein ~ "PCR"
    ),
    statistic = list(
      age ~ "{mean} ({sd})",
      weight ~ "{mean} ({sd})",
      height ~ "{mean} ({sd})",
      hemoglobin ~ "{mean} ({sd})"
    )
  )

4. Compare the proportion of diabetes mellitus by wave:

  1. Perform a graphical comparison.
Tip

To compare a proportion between groups, it is useful to use the position = "fill" argument of the geom_bar() function.

ggplot(data = divine, aes(x = dm, fill = covid_wave)) +
  geom_bar(color = "black", width = .8, position = "fill") +
  scale_x_discrete(name = "Diabetes Mellitus") +
  scale_y_continuous(name = "Percentage", labels = scales::percent) +
  scale_fill_discrete(name = "COVID-19 wave") +
  theme_bw()
  1. Perform the appropriate test to determine whether these differences are significant.
chisq.test(x = divine$covid_wave, y = divine$dm)

    Pearson's Chi-squared test with Yates' continuity correction

data:  divine$covid_wave and divine$dm
X-squared = 8.191, df = 1, p-value = 0.00421

5. Compare the age distribution by wave:

  1. Perform a graphical comparison using a density plot.
ggplot(data = divine, aes(x = age, fill = covid_wave)) +
  geom_density(alpha = .6) +
  xlab("Age") +
  scale_y_continuous(name = "Density") +
  scale_fill_discrete(name = "COVID-19 wave") +
  theme_bw()
  1. Repeat it using a box plot.
ggplot(data = divine, aes(x = covid_wave, y = age, fill = covid_wave)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  scale_x_discrete(name = "COVID-19 wave") +
  scale_y_continuous(name = "Age") +
  theme_bw()  +
  theme(legend.position="none")
  1. Perform the appropriate test to determine whether there are differences in age between groups.
Tip

Check the QQ-plot to determine if this numerical variable is normally distributed or not.

t.test(age ~ covid_wave, data = divine)

    Welch Two Sample t-test

data:  age by covid_wave
t = 4.6067, df = 575.08, p-value = 5.04e-06

95 percent confidence interval:
 3.197687 7.950920

              64.38103               58.80672

6. Compare the total leukocytes by wave:

  1. Perform a graphical comparison using a density plot.
ggplot(data = divine, aes(x = total_leukocytes, fill = covid_wave)) +
  geom_density(alpha = .6) +
  xlab("Total leukocytes") +
  scale_y_continuous(name = "Density") +
  theme_bw()
  1. Repeat it using a box plot.
ggplot(data = divine, aes(x = covid_wave, y = total_leukocytes, fill = covid_wave)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  scale_x_discrete(name = "COVID-19 wave") +
  scale_y_continuous(name = "Total leukocytes") +
  theme_bw() +
  theme(legend.position="none")
  1. Perform the appropriate test to determine whether these differences are significant.
Tip

Check the QQ-plot to determine if this numerical variable is normally distributed or not.

wilcox.test(total_leukocytes ~ covid_wave, data = divine)

    Wilcoxon rank sum test with continuity correction

data:  total_leukocytes by covid_wave
W = 103198, p-value = 0.7352
alternative hypothesis: true location shift is not equal to 0

7. Perform a comparison test on all variables as a function of the wave and add it to the table.

Tip

Use the add_p() function after using the tbl_summary() function previously used to create the table.

library(gtsummary)

divine |> 
  tbl_summary(
    include = -record_id,
    by = covid_wave,
    label = list(
      center ~ "Hospital",
      sex ~ "Sex",
      age ~ "Age",
      weight ~ "Weight",
      height ~ "Height",
      obesity ~ "Obesity",
      dm ~ "Diabetes mellitus",
      total_leukocytes ~ "Total leukocytes",
      hemoglobin ~ "Hemoglobin",
      c_reactive_protein ~ "PCR"
    ),
    statistic = list(
      age ~ "{mean} ({sd})",
      weight ~ "{mean} ({sd})",
      height ~ "{mean} ({sd})",
      hemoglobin ~ "{mean} ({sd})"
    )
  ) |> 
  add_p(
    test = c(age, weight, height, hemoglobin) ~ "t.test"
  )

8. Compute and interpret the effect size for the variables that showed statistically significant differences between waves. Use Cohenâs D if the variable is numeric and normally distributed. Use relative risk if the variable is categorical. Report the 95% confidence interval for each estimate.

#For the age:
library(effectsize)
cohens_d(age ~ covid_wave, data = divine)
Cohen's d |       95% CI
------------------------
0.33      | [0.20, 0.46]

- Estimated using pooled SD.

The difference is small (>= 0.2 and < 0.5).

#For the diabetes mellitus:
library(epitools)
rr <- epitools::riskratio(table(divine$covid_wave, divine$dm))
rr$measure
          risk ratio with 95% C.I.
            estimate     lower     upper
  1st wave 1.0000000        NA        NA
  5th wave 0.6911276 0.5368567 0.8897297

Diabetes mellitus has a relative risk of 0.69 [CI95%: 0.54, 0.89] meaning that the risk of diabetes mellitus is reduced by 31% ((1 - 0.69) * 100 = 31%) in the 5th wave compared to the 1st wave.
